It sounds a bit similar to the Biblical Babel's "Nimrod", whose etymology Rene Guenon traces to the arab-Hebrew "namar/nimir", which means "flecked animal" - as a tiger or leopard. Nimrod is a hunter, thus it fits. Man becomes hunter to man unless he sees himself as his neighbor.

Gene Wolfe has a story where men have started to call each other "Niman" as an almost honorific title, as a bastardization of "neighbor", because one must not do evil to his neighbor as per the Bible, but can burn his "Niman" alive if he wanted to.
"Nimrodian" thus refers to a temporal power unrooted from spiritual authority, like the warrior caste in India which revolted against the priesthood.

In Gene Wolfe's BoTNS, when Severian meets Typhon on the top of the world, not only is it a recreation of the New Testament scene of Satan tempting Christ in the mountains, but Typhon is the Greek name of Egyptian Seth, whose worshippers are the origin of the "counter-initiation"

Typhon was the ruler of the previous age or cycle of that world, just as the Jinn and Satan ruled the world before God's creation of man. Typhon is also an anagram for Python, the snake, albeit possibly just as coincidence. Adam's son Seth is the "opposite reading of the symbol".
